auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
legend("bottomright", legend = paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3)), col = "#1c61b6", lwd = 3)
```

### Log Model Summary 

The logistic regression model was used as the baseline model to predict lead conversion because it is highly interpretable and produces probabilities between 0 and 1. The model showed solid performance with 79% accuracy and an AUC of 0.822, indicating good ability to distinguish between converting and non-converting leads. Results show that medium and small tier accounts, management-level contacts, and high-intent actions such as “Contact Us,” “Live Demo,” and “Website Pricing” significantly increase the likelihood of conversion. In contrast, leads from Non-Life Science industries and several marketing channels such as email, events, and external demand generation showed lower conversion likelihood. Overall, the logistic model helped identify which variables influence conversion, providing interpretable insights that will guide further analysis with Random Forest to capture complex patterns and rank feature importance.

### Random Forest Model 

We decided to implement a Random Forest Model to our analysis to try to discover non-linear relationships in the data.  We have chosen to build 500 trees to learn from and aggregate our predictions to try to improve prediction accuracy.  Does industry and location truly have impacts on each other for conversion? Lastly, we are trying to determine which features are most important to model on.  Is there one feature over another that will have a stronger influence on conversion?  


```{r}
#data preparation 

set.seed(123)

train_index <- createDataPartition(Data3$Target, p = .7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- Data3[train_index, ]
test_data  <- Data3[-train_index, ]

train_data$Target <- as.factor(train_data$Target)
test_data$Target  <- as.factor(test_data$Target)

#random forest model 
rf_model <- randomForest(
  Target ~ acct.target.industry +
           acct.tier.rollup +
           acct.territory.rollup +
           contact.lead.title +
           last.tactic.campaign.channel +
           Priority,
  data = train_data,
  ntree = 500,
  importance = TRUE
)
```


```{r}

#generating predictions to test model performance 
print(rf_model)

rf_pred_class <- predict(rf_model, test_data)


rf_pred_prob <- predict(rf_model, test_data, type = "prob")[,2]


#confusion matrix to test sensitivity, accuracy, etc.  
confusionMatrix(rf_pred_class, test_data$Target)

#area under the curve graphic to score model performance 
roc_rf <- roc(as.numeric(test_data$Target), rf_pred_prob)
auc_rf <- auc(roc_rf)
print(auc_rf)

plot(roc_rf,
     col = "darkgreen",
     lwd = 3,
     main = "ROC Curve for Random Forest Model")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "gray")

legend("bottomright",
       legend = paste("AUC =", round(auc_rf,3)),
       col = "darkgreen",
       lwd = 3)

# Feature Importance
varImpPlot(rf_model)
```


### Random Forest Summary 

A Random Forest classification model was built using 500 trees and included predictors: industry, account tier, territory, lead title, campaign channel, and priority. The model achieved an accuracy of 83.1% with an AUC of 0.778, indicating good but slightly lower predictive performance than our logistic regression model. Again, the results showed the model to be effective at identifying non-converting leads but still struggled with identifying converting leads due to class imbalance.  Feature importance analysis highlighted which variables contribute most to prediction, helping uncover nonlinear relationships and interaction effects in the data.

### Text mining the job title field

Because MasterControl feels very strongly that job title is an important feature for this analysis, we decided to use some machine learning techniques to topic model the field and bin them using the results. We repeat the Random Forest model with this new feature and use it in a gradient boosted tree model to good effect.
```{r}
#factoring variables 
cat_vars <- names(Data2)[sapply(Data2, function(x) is.character(x) | is.factor(x))]

#removing unwanted variables 
cat_vars <- setdiff(cat_vars, 
                    c("QAL.ID", 
                      "qal.cohort.date", 
                      "contact.lead.id",
                      "next_stage__c"))
Mx_data <- Data2 %>%
  filter(solution_rollup == "Mx")

# split data into test and train
set.seed(123)

train_index <- createDataPartition(Mx_data$Target, p = .7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- Mx_data[train_index,]
test_data <- Mx_data[-train_index,]
```

Our first step is to tokenize the free text data field and perform necessary preprocessing to enable our LDA analysis.

```{r}
library(quanteda)
library(topicmodels)
library(tm)
library(tidytext)
library(quanteda.textstats)

# Tokenize and preprocess the text data
tokens <- train_data$contact.lead.title %>%
    tokens(remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE) %>%
    tokens_tolower() %>%
    tokens_remove(stopwords("en"))

cols <- textstat_collocations(tokens, min_count = 10)
tokens <- tokens_compound(tokens, pattern = cols)

tokens_test <- test_data$contact.lead.title %>%
    tokens(remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE) %>%
    tokens_tolower() %>%
    tokens_remove(stopwords("en"))

cols_test <- textstat_collocations(tokens, min_count = 10)
tokens_test <- tokens_compound(tokens_test, pattern = cols)


# Convert tokens to DFM
dfm_train <- tokens %>%
  dfm()

dtm_train <- convert(dfm_train, to = "topicmodels")

dfm_test <- tokens_test %>%
  dfm()

dtm_test <- convert(dfm_test, to = "topicmodels")

```

We will use the perplexity score to determine how many topics we would like to use for this analysis. We ended up going with 12 as it looks like a good local minimum. 
```{r}
k_values <- seq(2, 20, by = 1) # check each k value from 2-20
results <- sapply(k_values, function(k) {
  model <- LDA(dtm_train, k = k, method = "Gibbs", control = list(iter = 500))
  perplexity(model, newdata = dtm_test)
})

plot(k_values, results, type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE,
     xlab = "Number of Topics", ylab = "Perplexity",
     main = "Perplexity Elbow Chart")
```

#### LDA topic modeling results
```{r}
# LDA
title_lda_train <- LDA(dtm_train, k = 12, control = list(seed = 123))

title_lda_test <- LDA(dtm_test, k = 12, control = list(seed = 123))

# see the top 5 words that constitute each category
terms(title_lda_train, 7)

# add category column to dataframe

# get category for each document
title_category_train <- topics(title_lda_train)
title_category_test <- topics(title_lda_test)

train_data$title.category <- as.factor(topics(title_lda_train))

test_data$title.category <- as.factor(topics(title_lda_test))
```

We can now see if there is any relationship between the categories identified in the previous step and our target variable
```{r}
train_data %>%
  group_by(title.category) %>%
  summarise(
    ConversionRate = mean(Target),
    Count = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(ConversionRate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(title.category, ConversionRate),
             y = ConversionRate,
             fill = ConversionRate)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Mx Conversion Rate by Identified Title Category",
       x = "Title Category",
       y = "Conversion Rate") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "lightblue", high = "steelblue") +
  theme_minimal() +
  
  geom_text(aes(label = Count), hjust = -0.2, color = "black", size = 4)

```
We clearly see that topic 7 has a very high correlation with the target, they convert at a 21% rate, which is much higher than the standard 12.7%. In order to understand this topic further, we create a word cloud with the top words in this topic.

```{r}
library(wordcloud)
library(RColorBrewer)

# 1. Filter the dataset for category 7

subset_titles <- train_data$contact.lead.title[train_data$title.category == 7]

# 2. Create a text corpus
corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(subset_titles))

# 3. Clean the text (optional but recommended)
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))

# 4. Generate the Word Cloud
# Adjust 'max.words' and 'min.freq' based on your data size
wordcloud(corpus, 
          min.freq = 1, 
          max.words = 100, 
          random.order = FALSE, 
          colors = brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

```
This shows us that the job titles we are looking for are leadership roles within the quality assurance department of the companies we would like to market to.

