## Analysis Q and A 
### Level 1 Account Analysis Questions 

Q. Which types of accounts are best prospects for Mx? 

  A. Industries in Medical Devices and Blood & Biologics are more likely to convert to Mx.  

Q. Which manufacturing models are more likely to convert? 

  A. Based on our analysis consumer packaged goods, original equipment manufacturing, and CMO showed good volume as well as higher conversion rates.  In-house manufacturing has really high volume but standard conversion rates to existing value of 12.7%.  
  
Q. What site functions are likely to convert? 

  A. We did not explore this in enough detail. Feature engineering of site function will need to take place to showcase conversions in meaningful groups.   
  
### Level 2 Title Analysis 

Q. Which job titles convert best with account types? 

  A. We explored this at great length and repeatedly Management and Engineering prove to be the decision makes for our potential customers when exploring Master Control as a solution for their need.  These are the groups of people the Master Control Sales team should be engaging with.  
  
### Level 3 Cross-Sell Opportunties 
Q. Which accounts and titles are good for BOTH Qx and Mx products? 

  A. Based on our analysis for a great opportunity for cross selling would be a customer in the Blood & Biologics space as well as Medical Devices. Because of their heavy regulated nature both their quality management system as well as their manufacturing processes would benefit from the controlled, well documented solutions that Qx and Mx provide.  In these spaces it would be very benefical to the customer to have both required processes maintained in the same software that is able to speak to each other and draw results from.  
  
## Conclusion  

Through our analysis re-occuring themes appeared and were supported by the modeling. MasterControl's ideal customer profile are small to medium size companies that are in the Blood & Biologics and Medical Devices industries. Strongest conversion results for Mx appeared in EMEA and America Blood & Biologics, as well Japan Medical Devices.   Key decision makers that MasterControl should get their sales team in front of are Management and Engineering from perspective customers.   

We are confident that focusing on small and medium-sized blood and biologics companies in the Americas and EMEA, along with small and medium-sized medical device companies in Japan, will increase the MX conversion rate to 19%. If we include only those titles that are categorized into Topic 7 identified above, it raises to 21%. This targeted mix of company size, industry, and region has demonstrated higher conversion performance compared to the current average of 12.7%.  This represents a 49% relative lift in conversion rate.  

Reaching a 19% conversion rate for the Mx solution would align closely with the current performance of the Qx established product line, which has consistently delivered strong results over its 20+ year history.

## Executive Summary 

This analysis identifies the key drivers of lead conversion for the Mx product and defines a clear, data-backed Ideal Customer Profile (ICP) to improve targeting and performance. Through exploratory analysis and predictive modeling, we found that conversion is most strongly influenced by industry, company size, territory, and contact lead title.  

The highest-performing segments are small and medium-sized companies in the Blood & Biologics and Medical Device industries, particularly within the Americas, EMEA, and Japan. These segments demonstrate significantly higher conversion rates due to the regulatory complexity of their environments, which increases the need for Mx solutions. Within these accounts, Management and Engineering roles consistently show the strongest likelihood of conversion, indicating they are the primary decision-makers and should be the focus of sales engagement.

Predictive modeling supports these findings. A logistic regression model achieved an AUC of 0.82 and 78% accuracy, demonstrating strong predictive power and clear interpretability. Key positive drivers of conversion include high-intent actions such as “Contact Us,” “Live Demo,” and “Website Pricing” interactions, while lower engagement channels such as email, events, and external demand generation were associated with reduced conversion likelihood. The Random Forest model confirmed these patterns while highlighting additional non-linear relationships between variables, though with slightly lower predictive performance.

Based on these insights, we identified a refined ICP that achieves a conversion rate of 19%, compared to the current overall average of 12.7%, representing a substantial improvement in targeting efficiency. This level of performance aligns closely with the established Qx product line, reinforcing the strength and validity of this approach.

In conclusion, focusing sales and marketing efforts on regulated industries, prioritizing small to medium-sized accounts, targeting decision-makers in management and engineering roles, and emphasizing high-intent engagement channels will significantly increase Mx conversion performance and overall pipeline efficiency.

